text: I really do not understand why Hollywood considers it a sensible idea to replace previously popular and now tired franchises with an all female version with gender reversed jokes. It does nothing for the perception of women in Hollywood, other than annoy people who enjoyed the original film and leave a bad taste in your mouth at some of the awkward writing. Ghostbusters proved this.  The solution to not having enough strong female characters, is to give films a balanced cast that plays off of each character's strengths, rather than having one gender role defer to the other. You want to make another  Oceans film, then why not balance the cast with a few more strong female leads? Rather than going for the stock "wait I know, what if it was all women."   Improving women's roles is more about giving them a staging ground amongst other strong male leads, rather than making all the males in the film weak, to try and bolster the perception of the women. It's called nuanced writing, and Hollywood seem to have forgotten how that works, or become too lazy to bother.

text: I understand why some people might be upset at first, because from the outside at least it seems like nothing more than an exercise in Political Correctness, and it's been happening in lots of films/tv shows recently (e.g. Ghostbusters, Doctor Who, Planned Expandables All-Female Remake), but allow me to educate you - females exist. They aren't some out of left field minority, we're all actually birthed by females, and without them none of us could be here, so why are people surprised when they show up as the lead cast members in films. Also remakes themselves are nothing new (this is actually a spin-off but whatever), we should know by now that Hollywood has run out of ideas and maybe one of the only ways to keep things fresh is to change the gender of the cast. I also understand some peoples apprehensiveness that the movie will just suck, but this isn't by the same people that made Ghostbusters nor is it the same cast, I think with the right direction and cast this can be done right. Now I personally do not have any issue with them making an all-female remake in terms of the fact that I simply couldn't care less about the gender of the actors. I do think however that remakes like this can be more damaging for female equality than they are rewarding - why not make this movie but just call it something different, give it it's own voice? Either way some of the reasons people are bitching is rather silly because I can't see how casting females in something is trying to be politically correct. My final thought is this... maybe, JUST MAYBE, this movie will actually be good because it's well made and it's actually just enjoyable to watch... isn't that what we should merit films on?

text: Alright, look. There's no way of knowing that this movie is going to be good or bad based on a single trailer. I mean, look at Jumanji. That was a sequel/reboot that looked terrible, but actually received pretty good reviews. The only reason people are disliking this is because of the female leads, and you can't try to blame it on "full of cliches" or "this person can't act." Some people are just extremely butthurt about movies with female leads. So what if they are trying to empower women? Women do make up a minority in this world, but are recently gaining more power through movements such as #metoo; and based on the comments below, they need it. "So they have to remake every classic film with female casts ..I blame dishwashers," and other sexist crap like that (that's a real comment, by the way, from JRM Productions). As for the movie itself, it isn't just a "carbon cashgrab copy" of Ocean's 11. The basic plot is similar, but the characters and setup is different enough to set it apart from its predecessors. In the end, we don't know if this movie is going to be good or bad, but we shouldn't be sexist jerks about it. The world has enough hate already.

text: The problem with female versions of everything is that the female archetype/trope in film or any story telling is that there is always sex appeal--they're always another reincarnation of the Aphrodite. The appeal in the male Ocean's movies is that you had a wide range of archetypes, from dirty and lazy to tall and witty to old and wise to tiny and spunky. We don't have that here, we have one rehashed Aphrodite image after another. There will be panning make over fashion reveals, there will be cat-woman sex intimditation and there will be boredom.   I'm a female and a writer and an artist, and I can't help but be dissatisfied at the thought that writers only have one archetype women in film. Where's the angry short grandma, the disastrously careless scientist with bad hair, the tall beautiful temptress with a lisp or stutter. It can't be all the perfect image. Ocean's charmed us all because everyone of his team members were misfits, and he loved them all loyally.    A reused and recycled Kaling with her angsty Indian daughter role and another Bellatrix Lestrange don't cut it as creative story telling.

text: I can already hear the arguments concerning the similarities between this film and 2016's "Ghostbusters", but this time around, I think that Hollywood actually got the "gender swap" idea right.  In my opinion, "Ghostbusters: Answer the Call" was just too dumbed down and silly to be taken seriously, and as a result the suspense of disbelief constantly crumbled to pieces.  This film however, seems to have been made by a talented group of creators who actually took the concept and characters seriously, and as a result, it looks like a really good movie so far.  I'm very intrigued and want to see more, but before I commit to supporting this film in theaters, I'll need to see more trailers first.  I hope this film has a high level of quality throughout.  I guess only time will tell.  But for now, it earns a "thumbs up" from me.

text: It's funny how people complain about this being unoriginal but yet they praise the Clooney ones which not only were a remake but basically they made the same movie 3 times just by mixing it a bit, because the 3 with Clooney had the same basic concept with a similarly different frame. Get a grip, the message is not "Women can/should be able to do everything men do" or "We want to make a movie with only female actresses". Those may be parts of it and yes they benefit the Current feminist wave BUT these films are making you ACTIVELY think about inequality and gender issues simply by watching a trailer, something you wouldn't do with a movie that although has an original idea and interesting female roles is too subtle. Some people prefer subtle and leading by example instead of the constant conversations about the same issues that are being held and posted all over. Personally, I am one of those but at the same time I can see reason in ways that are very obvious about what they're doing and saying as long as it's made in good faith. There are a lot of ways to get to one point and there isn't necessarily a right way, so think about everything form factually correct opinions with thoughtful arguments and challenge your own viewpoint, don't just judge away. We live in an age in which we are being bombarded with these things from everywhere and we don't stop to think that if we didn't have our laptops and information didn't move as freely all around the world, we wouldn't have known about a film, a conversation or a protest for women's issues.

text: It looks like a totally fine movie. However, there is always something strange about these women-remakes. It is not simply the fact, that women play lead roles as strong characters but that they do it in movies that had an original all-male cast and that it is done in a way that just screams "oh let's show them men". There seems to be not really another reason to remake an all-male ensemble film with an all-female cast, then to perpetuate this message. To underline this message you have the catchy tunes of "these boots are made for walkin" which is just one of the go-to songs whenever someone wants to showcase strong femininity.   This is pretty bad for two reasons: first, you want these characters to be cool and tough but when the whole movie just becomes about "showing them men", the characters start to seem more needy and pathetic. Second, this just gives the impression that you don't know how to write interesting female characters without somehow referring to men.  Of course I don't know how the final movie will be. This is obviously just my impression from the trailer.

Look I get that you don't want your original movie to be changed but here's the thing and I'm speaking from my perspective, when I was younger, I just couldn't relate to movies where there was no female in an important role, I simply couldn't, it wasn't because I hated guys, it was because I found relating to guys difficult which is why I gravitated towards chick flit, now I'm sure the originals have a great story but for someone like me who has never experienced that, what's wrong with a studio creating a female version of the original so that we can enjoy it? The cast seems great, the trailer regardless of the fact that there was an original movie looks great, so of course I'm going to enjoy it. See I wouldn't mind it if men took movies like mean girls or juno or easy A or bridget jones or whatever and made an all men cast, I'm sure most men never gravitated towards those movies either and perhaps if a studio came out to make one you would enjoy it and relate to it. There's nothing wrong with promoting a movie or a franchise to a gender that wasn't the initial target.

text: This movie is nothing more than a publicity stunt, plain and simple. Based on the trailer it seems like it could be a fun and interesting heist movie with several very talented actresses, so then why is it a part of the Ocean's franchise and not trying to do its own thing? Because like Ghostbusters and Star Wars, having a pre-established and popular title will already guarantee an audience that will pay money to go see it. As well as trying to create a controversy by casting all women with the sole intent of pushing an agenda and by shitting on its predecessor. Sparking the controversy is a pre-planned move to get the word out and hype up the movie. By doing this, it will get people who love it to see the movie as a way of supporting their beliefs, and it will get people who hate it to see the movie out of curiosity to find reasons for hating it. It's such a fucking shame that we're living in a time where the majority of films being produced are just rehashes made to push an agenda, and not to simply entertain an audience.

text: This movie doesn't look particularly appealing to me, and yes it because it stars an all-female cast. Well, sort of. I have no issues with all-female, or predominantly female casts. What I can't stand are movies that have so much political and ideological baggage. Like with Ghostbusters, even if the movie weren't terrible, I still had little chance of enjoying it because of all the nonsense leading up to it.  I really wish that people would let movies stand on their own merit. I don't care if you think this is an SJW takeover, or a feminist dream. When movies like this are held to some stupid standard because people want to adopt them as ammo to fit some personal ideology, for me it is a sure sign of failure.  Anyway, best of luck to this movie, but I'll be skipping it I suspect.

text: So a couple of thoughts...  1) Sandra Bullock plays a sibling of Danny Ocean, so technically it‚Äôs not a remake. It‚Äôs a spinoff taking place within the already existing ‚Äòocean‚Äôs universe‚Äô. Matt Damon is even appearing as his character from the original trilogy, undoubtedly to further establish connectivity between the franchises.   2) The studio probably did a spinoff in order to avoid the ‚Äòfemale remake‚Äô label that would associate it with ghostbusters. However it‚Äôs the gender swap that makes people much more angry rather than seeing a remake, so they missed the mark there and surprise surprise the movie is getting hate right out of the gate, and will most likely bomb at the box office regardless of whether or not it is actually good.   3) Though I value equality among men and women, I am not a fan of gender swapped movies. Let me emphasize ‚Äúgender swapped‚Äù. I have absolutely no problem with movies with female leads, there‚Äôs nothing wrong with that. I just find that gender swapping (in this case an originally all male movie) takes away from the message of ‚Äúempowerment‚Äù (or whatever message the filmmakers want) in exchange for making it Social Commentary: The Movie, and forcefully jamming it down the throats of the viewers. I believe that female led movies would receive much less hate if they were original stories and concepts  or adapted from other female centred works. And it doesn‚Äôt seem to go both ways. I‚Äôd imagine if a gender swapped movie that featured males instead of females were released it would also be torn apart and likely be called sexist. However I don‚Äôt believe in hating movies outright before its been viewed and its quality measured, though we absolutely have the right to be optimistic or doubtful.  4) I personally don‚Äôt think this movie will do well commercially. But it might do alright critically, seeing as ghostbusters got a certified fresh 74% on RT (even though it was terrible). If oceans 8 turns out to be bad i feel it will likely still get good reviews as critics will be afraid of suffering backlash from the public ( likely the case with ghostbusters)  5) despite my skepticism, I really do that hope this movie ends up being genuinely good, and a welcome addition to the oceans series. But again, I‚Äôm doubtful.  These are only my personal opinions, if you agree, cool, if not, that‚Äôs okay too. Let‚Äôs just hope this film turns out well.

text: I love heist movies, but man oh man is this one gonna suck. Let me tell you why. Ocean's Eleven: We are going to steal 160 mil in CASH from a casino's underground bank vault. Impressive. Ocean's Twelve: We have to steal a a priceless Faberge egg from a museum while a another dick hole thief messes with us and actively trying to get us sent to jail and/or killed. Roundabout, but still impressive. Ocean's Thirteen: We are going to rig an ENTIRE CASINO so literally everybody wins and you lose. And we are taking your diamonds. Petty and impressive. Ocean's Eight: We are going to steal a necklace on a person... ARE YOU FUCKING SHITTING ME! You need 1 thief for that...maybe two. At least put the damn necklace in a high security bank vault or something.  Where is the ambition? Where is the scale? Ocean had to be 11, 12, 13 people. You don't need 8 people for a necklace. A heist movie should make you go, "How the fuck are they going to pull that off", not, "Get me an invitation and I'll get that necklace before the first drinks are served".  Reminds me of a sexist joke, "Why would women want to be on the same level as men? They should be aiming higher, which shows a lack of ambition...which is why they will never be better then men."

It was conceived by producer¬†Jerry Weintraub, Soderbergh and Clooney. Olivia Milch is to write the screenplay, and¬†Gary Ross¬†is to direct.[7][8]¬†Helena Bonham Carter,¬†Cate Blanchett,¬†Mindy Kaling¬†and¬†Elizabeth Bankswere later announced to star in the film,[9]though Banks' presence later turned out to be a rumor that did not materialize.[10]  During pre-production, the film's¬†working titlewas¬†Ocean's Ocho.[11]¬†In August 2016, Bullock, Blanchett, Bonham Carter and Kaling were confirmed to star, with¬†Anne Hathaway,¬†Rihanna,¬†Awkwafina¬†and¬†Sarah Paulsonclosing deals to fill the cast.[12][13]¬†During production on the film,¬†Dakota Fanning¬†and¬†Damian Lewis¬†were spotted on set, with Lewis's casting being confirmed in December 2016 and Fanning confirming her casting in March 2017.[14][15][16][17]  On November 11, 2016, Richard Robichaux was also cast in the film.[18]¬†That same month,¬†Matt Damon¬†confirmed he would appear in the film, reprising his role from the¬†Ocean's Trilogy.[19][20][21]¬†In January 2017,¬†James Corden¬†joined the cast as an insurance broker who begins to grow suspicious of the group.[22]¬†That same month, it was revealed¬†Anna Wintour,¬†Alexander Wang,¬†Zac Posen,¬†Derek Blasberg,¬†Lauren Santo Domingo,¬†Kim Kardashian,¬†Kendall Jenner,¬†Kylie Jenner,¬†Katie Holmes,¬†Olivia Munn,¬†Hailey Baldwinand¬†Zayn Malik¬†were announced to cameo in the film.[23][24][25][26][27]¬†That same month,¬†Richard Armitage¬†joined the cast of the film.[28]

text: Now, I see the reasons for people hating this and reasons for people loving it. -They are obviously going with the flow of women empowerment and I totally get why they would do that. I'm not in favor of this movement though because it's less about equality and more about being in charge of everything. The Ocean's' movies are classic movies that have starred a diverse cast of men and women. To replace the whole cast with women feels like it's less about a fun movie and more about an agenda.  -The guys complaining about the movie aren't doing it because females. They're doing it because they are fans of the previous movies and they dislike the idea of swapping to an all female cast. They're not ALL misogynists.  -However, I do notice that a lot of the females in the comments are completely misandrist. Not all of them are, but it seems like if you post something negative, it's " man tears, hehhehe" or something of the sort.   -Would you like it if Juno was remade with an all homosexual male cast? I don't think so. -How about a Bridesmaids remake with an all male cast? Sound appetizing? I didn't think so. -Kill Bill with a guy named Bill as the lead role?  -I got it! Let's remake The Hunger Games with Brad Pitt as Katniss. -Million Dollar Ben Affleck?  -This movie is not a good idea in my opinion and this "movement" is only dividing people.  -------This is coming from a FEMALE.

text: The comments section shows the degradation of humanity.  The very idea of a movie starring women is so offensive to some men they have to go out of their way to ruin it, just like they did with ghostbusters.  If you aren't threatened by the social change that brought about all female remakes then why are you wasting your time commenting here?  No one was threatened when Clooney was recast in a role made famous by Frank Sinatra, but if Sandra Bullock does it, people's minds explode!  Do you think they didn't make changes between the Sinatra version and the Clooney version?  Of course they did!  It was a completely different thing and yet no one cared.  It's fine to do whatever you want with a remake, just so long as you don't cast women in formally male roles, that's a bridge too far . . . what a bunch of sexist hypocrites.    You don't have a leg to stand on to be legitimately annoyed with this movie.  If you like heist movies it looks good, if you don't it looks bad.  End of story.  But people who don't like heist movies aren't watching this trailer because they aren't interested in the movie itself.  So if you hate heist movies and you're here, bashing it for having the gall to recast a movie with women, then just be honest about why you're here and why you're hating on it.  You're hating on it because you either hate women or don't give a fuck about women, to the point you won't even watch a movie that stars women.  That makes you a sexist.    If you're wasting your time posting around about this movie that makes you a sexist, an asshole and a horrible human being.

text: Resistance¬†fighters led by General¬†Leia Organa¬†evacuate their base when a¬†First Orderfleet arrives. Following an effective but costly counterattack led by¬†Poe Dameron, the Resistance vessels jump into hyperspace to escape, but the First Order follows using a tracking device.¬†Kylo Ren, Leia's son, destroys the Resistance support fighters, but hesitates to fire at the lead Resistance ship after sensing his mother's presence.¬†TIE fightersdestroy the bridge of the ship, killing several Resistance leaders and incapacitating Leia, leaving¬†Vice Admiral Holdo¬†in command. Disapproving of Holdo's passive strategy, Poe,¬†Finn,¬†BB-8, and mechanic¬†Rose Tico¬†embark on a secret plan to disable the tracking device.  Meanwhile,¬†Rey¬†has arrived on remote¬†Ahch-To¬†with¬†Chewbacca¬†and¬†R2-D2¬†aboard the¬†Millennium Falcon¬†to recruit¬†Luke Skywalker¬†to the Resistance. Disillusioned by the failures of the Jedi, Luke initially refuses, even after learning of¬†Han Solo's death. Unbeknownst to Luke, Rey and Kylo begin communicating with each other through telepathic visions. Prompted by R2-D2, Luke eventually agrees to teach Rey the ways of¬†the Force. Luke and Kylo give Rey differing accounts of the incident that turned Kylo to the dark side, with Luke confessing that he momentarily contemplated killing Kylo upon sensing that¬†Supreme Leader Snoke¬†had corrupted him, causing Kylo to destroy Luke's emergent Jedi Order in retaliation. Convinced that Kylo can still be redeemed, Rey leaves Ahch-To to confront Kylo without Luke. Luke prepares to burn down the Ahch-To Jedi temple and library, but he encounters¬†Yoda's Force ghost, who destroys the temple himself and encourages Luke to learn from his failure.  Holdo reveals her plan to discreetly evacuate the remaining Resistance members using small transports. Believing her actions to be cowardly and risky, Poe instigates a mutiny. Finn, Rose and BB-8 travel to Canto Bight and acquire the help of the hacker¬†DJ, who says he is able to help them disable the tracking device. They infiltrate Snoke's ship, but are captured by¬†Captain Phasma, though BB-8 manages to escape. Meanwhile, Rey lands on the ship, and Kylo brings her to Snoke, who reveals that he controlled the mental connection between her and Kylo as part of a plan to destroy Luke. Ordered to kill Rey, Kylo instead kills Snoke and works together with Rey to kill Snoke's guards. Kylo invites Rey to rule the galaxy with him, but Rey refuses. Using the Force, they struggle for possession of¬†Anakin Skywalker's lightsaber, which splits in two.  A recovered Leia stuns Poe, allowing the evacuation to begin. Holdo remains on the ship to mislead Snoke's fleet as all others attempt to flee to a nearby old¬†Rebel Alliancebase on¬†Crait. However, DJ reveals the Resistance's plan to the First Order, and the evacuation transports are targeted with heavy losses; Holdo sacrifices herself by ramming Snoke's fleet at lightspeed to stop the barrage. Rey escapes in the chaos, while Kylo declares himself new Supreme Leader. BB-8 frees Finn and Rose, who escape after defeating Captain Phasma, and join the survivors of the evacuation on Crait. When the First Order arrives, Poe, Finn, and Rose lead a charge with old¬†speeders. Rey draws the TIE fighters away with the¬†Falcon, while Rose saves Finn from a suicide run against the main enemy cannon, which blasts a hole in the Resistance fortress.  Luke appears and confronts Kylo alone so that the surviving Resistance fighters can escape. Kylo orders the First Order forces to fire on Luke to no effect, then engages Luke in battle himself. Kylo strikes Luke twice with his lightsaber, only to learn that he has been fighting Luke's Force¬†projection. Luke defiantly tells Kylo that he will not be the last Jedi, while Rey uses the Force to help the remaining Resistance fighters escape via the¬†Falcon. Back on Ahch-To, an exhausted Luke peacefully dies and becomes one with the Force. Leia reassures everyone that the rebellion has all that is needed to rise again. On Canto Bight, one of the children that helped Finn and Rose escape grabs a broom with the Force and gazes hopefully up into space.

It just seems as if they are simply "remaking" these movies because they think the movie didn't care about diversity enough. So now we need to "fix" it. text: People are attacking others in this comment section who are frustrated that Art has become poisoned with political agenda. I‚Äôve never personally met a man who was attracted to a weak woman or did not enjoy watching strong female roles. The reason people are frustrated is because it has become obvious to them when a plot and casting has been purposely devised in order to appease political agenda and political correctness to the detriment of artistic quality.  We can tell when something is forced or pushed on us. Compare the strong female lead in Star Wars Rogue One who kicks butt without having to prove anything, against the Rey character of the Force Awakens shaking away Finn‚Äôs hand when he tries to pull her to safety, Captain Phantasma character written as male and changed to female, Andy Serkis talking about Snoke‚Äôs fear of a feminine power. This is when the agenda poisons the art and true creativity, and leads it away from the story to be told and into our contemporary societal issues.  When I write a story, the female characters kick ass because that‚Äôs what appeals to me and that is what my male characters find attractive, like Lagertha in Vikings- I don‚Äôt like the useless, pretty princess, I like the shield maiden who can hold her own. But I don‚Äôt put pen to paper feeling that I must write a character as such and such, because then it‚Äôs not my story, it becomes someone else‚Äôs. Truly strong female characters have nothing to prove...... that‚Äôs real empowerment - not needing to force your ego or point upon others in order to prove anything, because you know what you are and are not insecure. There is no need to turn art into a battleground of the sexes.

Oceans 11 with Clooney etc.¬†Is a love story that involved Clooney¬†enlisting his con friends into doing something, robbing a casino,¬†that would result in him getting his love back. It wasn't marketed as "A male movie"...it simply had characters portraying cool criminals.   Last time I checked the stats - armed robbery, theft, fraud - was a male dominated game. So seems accurate.  The women who appear in the Clooney led Ocean films, are either super talented art dealers - Julia Roberts or anti-fraud pro's¬†and daughter of legendary thief¬†- Catherine Zeta Jones,¬†FBI or¬†CIA - Matt Damon's mom character. Then we have Al Pacinos hotel and casino manager/PA¬†who was played by Ellen Barkin. So, no women portrayed as anything other than successful in their field, who hold positions of power and authority. Also no women whom we can view as evil or¬†wrong - benedict, Willie, The Night¬†Fox.  ¬†Yet we now have the assumption that those films were purely made to be enjoyed by males, and are sexist.   I fear¬†Oceans 8¬†will turn into an oestrogen driven man hating movie, where Sandra Bullock will¬†get one over on the¬†"man" who wronged her. with mommy jokes and duckling to swan scene included. However,¬†its unlike Ghostbusters,¬†in that it¬†doesn't appear to¬†be the "selling point" that it is a female remake¬†film, the heist seems to be the focus, they just happen to be women. text: The fact that it's ALL women is a pretext because there's equal vitriol about a woman leading the new Star Wars trilogy, two Asian female heroes in The Last Jedi, and a woman leading in Rogue One. Moreover, Ocean's is not even a good franchise. All those A-list celebrities yielded the following Rotten Tomatoes scores: Ocean's 11 (82%), Ocean's 12 (55%), Ocean's 13 (70%). Similarly, Ghostbusters was 97%, but Ghostbusters 2 was 53%. At 74%, the all-female remake was substantially better than the sequel. Simply put, if hating reboots and sequels is your MO, please channel your anger toward killing the Coming to America sequel. Thanks.

It was a reboot based off of the classic Ghostbusters but with full on woman replacing men. Feminism does exist with some movies (etc.), but Wonder Woman was already her own thing, she doesn't try to reboot a man or men. WW is pretty OP in the new DC movies but at least they don't go off rubbing it in your face. With Justice League, that wasn't the case even though that movie wasn't so amazing (if anyone gets me) because of Bruce being the reliable one to make the team. In WW, it was her movie and in Justice League, she didn't take too much of the spotlight. WW is a pretty decent film whether high praise or not, compared to the other recent live action DC movies. So those men trying to make a point should just quit it. feminists who call themselves "woman" should make a name for themselves instead of rebooting "men". text: The reason why people, including myself, are worried about this movie is because of movies like Ghost busters that had an extremely obvious feminist agenda (so pretty much saying that 'look women are cool too they can do all the things the boys can and more in the same thing').  Now I have no problem with female leads, Atomic Blond is an amazing movie and one of my favorite spy movies ever, but what we see from this trailer is the fact that they only made this an Oceans movie without any men just to say the same thing as what the  ghost busters were going for.  If you want to do a heist movie with an all female cast then go for it but don't try to make it a political statement by doing an unneeded carry on  of an already good series that wasn't hinted at or even mentioned.  Just do a good movie that happens to have most of it's cast female, don't make it about the fact they are a female version of a pre-existing  franchise, which is what they are clearly doing.    And that's why people aren't looking forward to this movie.  Btw I am probs gonna watch it cause this isn't that bad of a trailer, besides it being an unneeded Oceans movie and I am missing a good heist movie aaannd it could be good, but i just wanted to explain why people are mad. =)

text: You know, if this sequel/spin-off wasn't centered around Danny Ocean's sister and her female heist team but some long lost son of his and all his male buddies, I'm sure there would be people saying "this is gonna suck, why did they have to do this, etc" but not once would the gender of the cast be an issue anyone would bring up as a reason not to watch it/why it would suck. If you're not a fan of multiple sequels or spin-offs or you just think it was unnecessary to revisit this universe, that's totally valid but if it's purely for the reason that this main cast is female and you would otherwise enjoy it if it wasn't, maybe you have some re-evaluating to do. Hollywood revisits cinematic universes all the time to cash in on the popularity of a franchise. Multiple/belated sequels and spin-offs are not a new thing. If you think such films are of a lesser cinematic quality or just not your thing, that's understandable but the gender of the cast doesn't lessen the cinematic value, however.

text: Representation is important, but we don't have to remake or reboot everything with all female casts. What we need is fresh, new media with representation. I have no doubt this will probably be littered with the strong, independent woman stereotype. I'm hoping that's not what it is, but it's looking pretty transparent already. Especially seeing that they are robbing the Met Gala for fashion and money. I want to see representation that's realistic. I'm not offended about the past and lack of representation in media, but we need to move forward. I'm not sure that this is what "moving forward" looks like. It's not just about the actors, but rather who produces the movies, directs them, etc. If everything behind the film is run by men then I'm pretty sure the outcome of this is going to be predictable and vapid.

This is a good idea to make because you've seen one dynamic of those heist films now you see another.  You didn't hear people shouting sexism that Oceans 11, 12, 13 is primarily a male cast because for one, people are used to it and two, it wasn't sexist it was just that it was about a group of guys, that was the dynamic.  Well guess what now you get a new dynamic, it may not be as good as the first because let's face it those first few were the first and they were really freaking good(because Soderbourgs a genIUUUUss) but this could be cool too. text: Seeing some comments about how the trilogy was the original. I would like to offer some clarifying information. The original Ocean's 11 came out in 1960, starring Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Samuel Davis Jr and other actors. The Ocean's 11 starring George Clooney, Brad Pitt, Matt Damon and other actors came out in 2001. The original, in 1960, had no sequels. The sequels that followed the 2001 version were based on the 2001 version. The trilogy is not the original. In any case, I am looking forward to this version. Have a nice day.

text: To anyone complaining about why this exists, let me explain why many are excited for this and hyping it up (clears throat) (note that the following is to make above about disproportionate representation in Hollywood and not the quality of the following titles):  Notable blockbuster titles with a majority of all female leads that aren't bland interests in semi recent memory: Ghostbusters (bleh), Wonder Woman, Hidden Figures, Girls Night Out...?  In contrast to:  The Fate of the Furious, The Magnificent Seven, The Hitman's Bodyguard, American Assassin, American Made, The Accountant, The Foreigner, Just Getting Started, The Dark Tower, Transformers: The Last Knight, Baywatch, King Arthur, The Mummy, Overdrive, 6 Days, Acts of Vengeance, First Kill, xXx: Return of Xander Cage, Unlocked, 24 Hours to Live, Wheelman, Cops and Robbers, Dunkirk, Hacksaw Ridge, Batman vs Superman, pretty much every marvel movie, Assassins Creed, Sausage Party, Jack Reacher: Never Go Back, 13 Hours, The Nice Guys, Gods of Egypt...  I could go on for literally days but you get the idea. Note that I'm taking about major blockbusters with a MAJORITY female cast (not just one female character solely there to break up the sausage fest and mostly get killed or kidnapped to give wonder bread protagonist something to angst and grit his teeth over) that have major studio backing, star power, and decent marketing. I'm not saying this is 100% going to be awesome (it's not out yet- so people shouldn't be assuming the opposite either) but movies like this are important to lift up, because they're already starting at a lower level than every other snarky white-guy lead action/heist movie out there because you already have many a douchebag dissing it because they're under some vague impression that women are trying to "take over" something that's "theirs" by trying to do what they've been doing to decades.

text: I really like Sandra Bullock, so it's hard to take a shit on the idea of this movie. However, "Ocean's 8?" So you had to make an all female one because the Ocean's Eleven (the only one that matters) didn't have females in it? Why not just take a similar cast and make an original idea? For the people that say, "Well, I don't think this has anything to do with the 'Ocean's' movies." Really? It's in the title, with a different number, and it's based on the same exact concept: a group of professional thieves come together to rip off something super valuable. And to the people who say, "you just don't want women to do movies like these." Untrue, in fact most fans loved Charlize Theron from The Italian Job for example. Her character fit perfectly in that story. There's plenty of movies out there with male leads that we(men) take a huge shit on because it sucks; the idea sucks, the direction sucks, the cast sucks. Just getting tired of Hollywood looking for "woman power" movies. We (men) loved Sigourney Weaver of Alien(s), Linda Hamilton of The Terminator series, Carrie Anne Moss of The Matrix, Uma Thurman of Kill Bill, etc. So it's not about hating on women, it's about Hollywood basically remaking old greats but recasting with all females for the purpose of pushing feminism. It's supposed to be about art, not political/social agendas. I'll give it a chance, because again, Sandra Bullock is a fantastic actress. But come on! Come up with something freaking original!

text: This is so sad. Women have had tons of awesome female characters, in action, drama, comedy, etc. All these reboots-with-women movies just give the impression to people that women can't do cool things without nabbing a story from a different, male-led, franchise, while there've been plenty of good examples of this stretching back (probably far, far more, but this is purely my limited movie watching experience) to at least Alien in 1979. Plenty of recent examples from English-language to foreign. just in the last few years. People seem extra whiny about action stars which bugs me because, yeah they're movies, but I have to point out that that just statistically, it's more likely for a guy to be in those sorts of roles, both in wanting to do action movies as actors, and as characters, where men are more likely to be involved in this sort of thing in real life, so here's some strong, female-led/co-led films right off the top of my head, both in English and abroad, examples of non-pandering, believable female character who aren't just "women being men." Truth is that women are different to men, but no less brave, daring, and intelligent. More movies should acknowledge this difference, which doesn't prevent them from being badass. Here's some off the top of my head (dozens I'm doubtless missing, just from  last few years, but I''m not  going  to make this post longer than it is already going to be.  Feel free to post others to contribute.  Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri (2017 (better get an Oscar nom)) The Villainess (2017, South Korea) The Handmaiden (2016, Soth Korea) The Neon Demon ( 2016) Hush (2016) 10, Cloverfield Lane (2016) Arrival (2016) Raw (2016 (okay I haven't seen it but looks awesome and people loved it) Room (2015) Anomalisa (2015 (robbed of Oscar for animated film by Inside Out)) The Assassin (2015, China) Assassination (2015, South Korea) Ex Machina (2014 (It's a robot but AI so I count it) Gone Girl (2014) The Babadook (2014) Proxy (2013) Prometheus ( 2012 (fuck you I liked it) Melancholia (2011) The Host (2006, Soth Korea) Lady Vengeance (2005, South Korea) KILL FUCKING BILL (2003, 2004) Monster (2003) Joint Security Area (2000, South Korea) Three Colors Trilogy (1993--1994, Fench. Polish) Silence of the Lambs (1991)  I could go on and on and on and on with movies before the dates I listed, as well as movies in between the most recent years. Just make something original; I'm no feminist, but it's so much better for both movie quality and the perception of women's opportunities in the industry (which would satisfy -- as in shut up -- feminists on the subject). Anything to stop this female-only reboot business going on and give us more original movies with actual inspiration behind them.

text: I'm really worried about this film not being any good. Just based on the trailer, it seems like it doesn't have the same style, themes, or mood that the trilogy did, which is why I think it looks like it really shouldn't be an Oceans movie. It looks as if it would be absolutely great as a standalone film in its own universe, just not as a part of the Oceans series.  I really really really want it to be well made, as I want all the films under the Oceans series name to be good, but the fact that Danny is dead is a huge turn off for me. The chemistry that the original cast had was absolutely perfect for those films and the mood they had. I'm curious to see if the cast of this one can keep up with that. There's no doubt that they've got a lot of great A-list actors in it, but just because they're great actors doesn't mean they're a great fit for the film, and I would really like to see them portray their roles well.  All in all, I'm not all that excited about an Oceans film without George Clooney/Danny Ocean as the main character, but I'll be willing to give it a watch after it's left the theater. If I hear that it's really good when it comes out, I'll be a lot more inclined to see it in the Cinema. Here's to hoping that they execute this film well, and that it doesn't become another disappointing attempt at a series revival.

text: The reason a lot of people are mocking this movie isn't that it has a female cast. Plenty of movies have had female casts, and no one gave a shit. The problem with this movie (and Ghostbusters 2016) is that it feels like the writers have tried to shoehorn women into roles that just make more sense for men.  Men tend to be more reckless, they tend to be more interested in tinkering with things (like vaults and security systems), and they tend to be greedier, as well. Thus, they make more sense as thieves. Not that you could never write a plausible female thief, but a group of 8 of them? Come on.

text: The only comparison I can think of that works between this and Ghostbusters (2016) is simply the all-female angle.  But if you think harder about it, this isn't nearly as cynical a cash-grab.  Oh sure, it's trying to use the Ocean's name for brand-recognition, but (1) Ocean's has never been as beloved a cultural phenomenon as Ghostbusters to begin with, so that makes this easier to accept, and (2) Ocean's doesn't hinge on balancing two very different genres like Ghostbusters does with horror and comedy (and which the 2016 film failed spectacularly at).  Ocean's have always just been heist movies, and their most distinct quality is that they're way bigger team-ups than most heist movies are (though The Sting would beg to differ, even if that's more of a con movie than a heist movie XD).  So as long as it works as a heist movie, this'll be just fine.  This isn't some "betrayal" of the series, guys, and Ghostbusters didn't strictly fail because the team was all-female.  It failed because Sony had no bucking clue how to make a Ghostbusters movie and did the most boring and predictable things they could with the cast they had.  So give this one a chance, it already looks a million times more interesting than Ghostbusters 2016 ever did.

text: These things never cease to annoy simply because they are so contrived. People are told clearly and firmly that this is a cheap attempt fueled by a cynical lust for easy money and a skewed and forced sense of social justice.  And because the intent was never pure and honest to begin with, neither will the movie feel that way. It won't feel like art, but like a cheap and forced attempt for our money and attention. It deserves all our disdain and more and I hope that this unreasonable bs could finally stop.  Look if you wake up from a dream that involved all women or had an epiphany that just screamed "women" go for it and create your original art for the world to enjoy. But don't make some hacky contrived bs then call us misogynistic for not taking the bait. What a bad time we live in, where on all sides and ideologies, passion comes firmly before any consideration for rationality and truth.  Edit: And what a bad time when you can make yourself feel like a "good man or good woman", by denying yourself the natural wisdom and rationality that talks against the forced and contrived ways of thought. Jesus, culture never moves freely.

text: This film has a stink to it that most people can't explain so they immediately jump on the most basic interpretation, which you see in the form of previous comments, in a nutshell "this film is sexist towards men", "they are ruining the original", and so on.  In actuality, I believe there is a little more to it and if you'll follow me, I'd like to try explain why the FILM is actually WAY more sexist.  First, I'd like to point out that while the male version of first Ocean's film had the guys rob a casino, the female version appears to be stealing a necklace. Because I guess they figure woman like shiny things, so lets have them steal jewelry. Not patronizing at all... Next, why is this an Ocean's film to begin with? Why not just make a simple Heist movie with women and call it something else? Answer: They wanted to the namebrand and the controversy.  The makers of this film don't give a shit about equal representation. They want a quick buck by piggybacking off an established franchise and the free publicity from the outrage. Fools on both side can't see that they are being used to promote this film. Same thing happened with Ghostbusters. You're all being played.

text: Here's a question.  Did anybody even ask for another remake of Ocean's 11.   The George Clooney remake was pretty blegh even with the ensemble cast it amassed.   This is safe feminism.   You take a group of women and cast them in a remake of a franchise made successful by men,  if it succeeds it's empowering,  if it fails you blame the strawman that is misogyny.   Look at Ghostbusters,  the whole movie was centered around the fact it had women cast,  rather than just writing a good movie.   But let's ask go deeper.  What does it say about Hollywood's interpretation of feminism that they don't give a cast like this their own franchise to build on,  and instead pass an already established one.   Could it be Hollywood doesn't think these women can hold up their own franchise on name and talent alone and are instead looking to bank on the Ocean's 11 name to get people in theatres rather than genuine interest in an all female ensemble cast with an original story?.

The last 2 where a joke because a decent new supergirl or batwoman movie would be awesome because they are original female characters loved by millions, even if they didn't already have male counterparts we still wouldn't want to see them swapped for male roles, just make good films about original female characters, or at most swap them for characters that aren't absolutely beloved by everyone, stop with the reboots and sequels of great still well known franchises ruining good franchises just to throw more women in there is already obvious and stale, we wouldn't want to watch an alien reboot where ripley was a man or terminator where sarah was now seth there is no bias we just want originality or characters we know and love, how hard is that to grasp for hollywood?  Rebecca Buck - Tank Girl Ripley - Alien Sarah connor - Terminator Wonder Woman Captain Marvel (looks awesome even before release so i'm adding it xD) Alice - Resident Evil (the first few are good films) The Bride - Kill Bill Hit-Girl - Kick-Ass (easily needs a solo movie) Trinity from the Matrix (and they are talking sequels so she could easily hold a solo movie herself) Princess leia - Star Wars (did she really ever feel like a background character who couldn't take care of herself?)  These are just from my favourite movies that have female main characters that I thought kicked ass, I could never see a man taking up these characters roles, but hey if you want to swap some genders fine but do it right, starbuck in the reboot of battlestar galactica was great because it was written so well and the franchise had been dead for decades, it had its devoted fanbase but it was far from it's millions, but they didn't gender swap everyone for the sake of it they thought it through,   like the ghostbusters... while saying it is still in the same universe "in the 80s 4 scientists" then making all the new female characters basically just like the original characters in terms of backgrounds, spengler..... but not related to egon? dana... as some crazy scientist woman with an accent.. using the original actors but not as there original characters and killing one off (likely because it was obvious murray wanted nothing to do with anymore of the movies which is why he alone halted the production of a ghostbusters 3 almost his whole life) it was just a mess of pointlessness with callbacks and constant saturday night live adlibbing... I know the original actors all worked on SNL but the comedy the did on there was far from the dry comedy used in the original ghostbusters.  Anyway i've ranted on WAY too long for a comment on a simple sequel movie and I feel like a bit of a cun.t for that but hey maybe many feel the same way, from the likes to dislikes i'm guessing so, and I doubt all of them are men as plenty of women see how bad some of these movies are becoming to it isn't a sex thing...... text: I liked the Ocean movies. They were as clever as they were dumb, though very entertaining. But they sort of hinted at each character having a history in crime. My only concern is this: Will they convince me that Danny's wife, who hated his criminal ways, and scorned him for at least one movie, has the same set of skills he had? the ability to find, vet, and employ a team to get the job done. Either heists were how they met, and she chose to get out while he chose to keep stealing. or she picked it up through osmosis. Honestly, i would love this movie if it was this premise, but nothing to do with the Oceans. women being awesome is awesome xD. i worry this is a contrived gender swap. Warner Bros. sold Rotten Tomatoes, but Warner Bros. still holds a minority stake with the company. text: First of all, this series didn't need to exist past the first film. They all followed the same exact formula and weren't very interesting to watch after the first. Basically boils down to, two characters decide to pull a radical heist, they have to recruit talent for each scenario in the form of a montage, they train for the heist montage, they perform the heist montage, it appears as though they fail the heist to add artificial stakes, they reveal information to the audience the writers intentionally kept from them so they can pull off an unexpected twist to show how they were successful. BOOM! Ocean's movie. Predictable and doesn't carry an entire franchise. Even worse is how the film's design is to show you every plan for the heist except the most important one that will guarantee their success. It's a cheap plot twist that relies on withholding information rather than misdirection and smart writing.  Secondly, while I'm not against an all female cast, this one in particular makes no sense. There is literally no reason for their team to be made up of entirely women especially during the recruitment process because pulling off a large scale heist that requires precision timing and experts in their respective roles means you hire the right person for the job because of their skill, not their gender. I'm all for equality but that means assimilation not segregation. You want to promote female diversity in film? Cast more women in your project along side the males. Otherwise this is forced feminism catering to one audience over the other.  It's the same reason why I think BET is a stupid channel. Having an all black channel and an all black awards show promotes segregation. Why would we come this far just to go backwards? We keep talking about equality but no one actually wants to put forth the effort in assimilation. They all want their own things. So we have the women's channel, black channel, Latino channel, Korean channel. We can't keep creating little entertainment pockets that cater to one audience. That is literally the exact opposite of equality.

text: Second paragraph of the oceans 8 review on fandom wikia- "Here‚Äôs a dirty secret about the Ocean‚Äôs movies: the characters don‚Äôt actually matter. People don‚Äôt come to these movies because they are invested in the character of Linus Caldwell. They watch these films because they like seeing Matt Damon play that character. The same is true of Ocean‚Äôs 8. This is a stellar ensemble of eminently watchable actresses who are all having a blast. Yes, Sandra Bullock is playing the sister of Danny Ocean but that‚Äôs so tangential that it really doesn‚Äôt matter. What matters is Bullock‚Äôs confidence and unflappable coolness."  BS Ocean's was always about the characters each of them were played an integral part that makes the story more intriguing. We aren't watching it because who the actors (or PC SJW reboots in Ocean's 8 case) we are watching it because the actors fit the characters that were developed. We shouldn't just force a gender swap because it's 2018.  TLDR Ocean's is supposed to be a fun action movie that makes you care about the story and I haven't watched these movies just because they are action movies. author: Mohammad Gh

text: I'm definitely not one to yell "no way" every time a story takes a few liberties to stretch into the implausible.  But Oceans 8 starts taking on water from the get-go, starting with the hard-to-miss runway-worthy makeup job Bullock sports before the parole board. From there, every attempt to patch the film's breached hull only hastens her demise.  The movie capsized early enough in the film that we should have known to walk out and reclaim our evening when a key vehicle of the con (involving a special 3D printer) is so preposterous that it is insulting.  They'd have been better off rubbing a genie out of a bottle and getting their three wishes.  We sat there hoping at least the action would build pace and save this wretched thing, but it never did.  It was tiresome in every regard and scoff-worthy at every turn.  In the car, on the way home, as my wife and I lamented the loss of two hours of a Tuesday summer night, I found myself explaining to her where the term "jumping the shark" came from.

text: The feminist idiot troll VioletFlameMusic is still hopelessly trying to hype Ocean's 8 even though the numbers for the film are not impressive. Ocean's 8 has earned $254,885,183 globally at the time of this writing, but we need to subtract some important numbers from that global gross total.  The average split with distributors is 49% with the lowest reported split being 43% which changes every week as the film continues to be shown. The longer the film stays in cinemas the more money the distributors keep. Also keep in mind the cost of marketing and distribution of the film which costs millions. Finally the original cost to film Ocean's 8 is reported to be $70 million. Black Panther has earned $1,346,567,144 globally.  Avengers: Infinity War has earned $2,042,294,443. Ocean's 8 has a long way to go to be considered impressive at the box office. Remember that Warner Bros. owns 30% of Rotten Tomatoes so the positive reviews can't be trusted. text: I loved the ocean's trilogy so much, this movie just hurt my feelings when watching it. The high class was gone. And we got a copycat heist of the original 11 and 13 combined. I missed the grain of real film, they used a digital camera and it made it look cheap. I missed the biggest stars of the movie and that is location, location, location. The MET was a good location but the "only" good location. I missed the cryptic conversations between Danny and Rusty, there unique chemistry was pure cinema. You felt a genuine friendship. There was so much more 8 could do... Better location scouting, interesting dialogue, and more focus on character development. I need to emphasize with the characters not just wacht a heist unfold. This movie needed a better "want"( a reason to heist in the first place). It was always about the style and the flair and not the heist itself. Very disappointed in this cash grab.. If they make a 9, I hope, really hope they read what the fans had to say.

text: For those of you who have seen Ocean's 8 the picture, try to recall the last scene. Sandra sits down on a wooden bench which faces a wall of multiple engraved tombs. As she pours her beverage into a martini glass, pay close attention to the tombstone to her lowest bottom right.    Engraved into the granite facing appear the words 'Helga M. Meyer' 1992 ‚Äì 2010 as the date of birth and death of the deceased. Sandra's biological mother sadly passed on April 4, 2000--her name was as it appears on the tombstone in the movie -- Helga M. Meyer.    The last words of dialog spoken as Sandy gazes directly into the camera in this final scene right before it fades to black and the end credits begin roll are-- "you would've loved it."    This is no coincidence. The final scene is cleverly crafted as a sentimental homage to her deceased mother who didn't get to see her daughter's best work, and who was by death denied the opportunity to witness her beloved daughter receive an Academy Award.    Although Helga may not be with you in the physical form Sandra, she will always be with you in spirit and is aware of what a remarkable woman you've become artistically-- including the adoptions of two beautiful children in desperate need of someone in this cruel world to want them, to need them, to love them.    Well done Sandra... Well done.
